Bind mounts.

A bind mount maps a path on your host directly into a container. There's no Docker-managed storage and no copying; the container sees the host's actual bytes. For example, you run n-ginx with dash v, a host site directory, colon, the n-ginx web root, colon, r-o.

This serves the host directory as n-ginx's web root. Edit a file on the host, refresh the browser, and you see the change. The r-o makes it read-only inside the container, which is a good default when the container shouldn't be writing to your source tree.

The classic dev workflow is what bind mounts are made for. First, keep your source on the host, where your editor and git live. Second, run the app in a container with that source bind-mounted in. Third, either restart on each change, or use a hot-reloading runtime, like node-mon, flask reload, or u-vicorn reload.

The trade-off is that a bind mount hardcodes the host path. So the same docker run command won't work on a teammate's machine unless their layout matches. That's exactly why production deploys use volumes, not binds, and why Compose files, in module six, use relative paths that resolve against the project root.

Two gotchas to remember. First, there's no image-content copy. Unlike a fresh named volume, a bind mount silently masks whatever the image had at that path. Mount over slash app, and the image's slash app disappears behind the host's, possibly empty, directory. Second, ownership surprises: files the container writes are owned by the container's user I-D on the host, the classic, why is this owned by root, that section ten unpacks. The rule of thumb: bind mounts for code you're actively editing, and volumes for data you're keeping.
